Here's an example of a C++ function that converts a std::string containing Markdown to HTML:

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <sstream>
#include <iostream>

std::string markdown_to_html(std::string str) {
    // First, split the input string into lines.
    std::vector<std::string> lines = std::split(str, "\n", std::string::npos);

    // Then, for each line, replace certain characters with their HTML entities.
    for (auto& line : lines) {
        line = line.replace("&", "&amp;");
        line = line.replace("<", "&lt;");
        line = line.replace(">", "&gt;");
    }

    // Finally, join the lines back into a single string and return it.
    return std::string(lines.begin(), lines.end());
}
```
This function takes a string containing Markdown and returns a string containing HTML code. It works by splitting the input string into lines, then replacing certain characters with their HTML entities, and finally joining the lines back together to form a single string. The returned string can be used in a web page or any other context where HTML is needed.

